result.execSummary:
The defendant Francisco Carbajal-Vicuna was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Concurrent with: Waushara Co Case No. 2015CF000112

miscConds.notes: Costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.

Defendant is prohibited from having any contact with Y.C-G. and/or L.C-G.  Any communications with Y.C-G. are to be via text message only and solely limited to matters pertaining to the child in common.  Defendant is prohibited from possessing any weapons or utilizing any device in such a manner that is capable of causing injury to another.  Defendant is to complete an Anger Management Program or a Domestic Abuse Alternatives Program as can be coordinated through the supervising agent, if in fact available due the language barrier, together with any follow through counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent as part of that programming.
DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.

Total Restitution ordered in the amount of $5330.93 is ordered repaid as follows:  $350.00 owed directly to the victim and  $4980.93 owed to the Crime Victim Compensation Program.  Cash Bond previously posted in the amount of $150.00 has been applied and disbursed directly to the victim by the Clerk of Circuit Court, leave a balance due to the victim of $200.00.  In the event that the Defendant is revoked or discharged from probation with outstanding financial obligations, the supervising agent shall notify the Court 10 days prior to the revocation or discharge.  A civil judgment shall be entered against the Defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement action will be used to collect the debt.
